---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Footer from '../components/layout/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Thesis — Bird Candy"
  description="Why Bird Candy believes in open lexicons: when data is open, you win on functionality, not on your data model."
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="pt-20 pb-16 lg:pt-30 lg:pb-20">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-8">Thesis</p>
    <h1 class="text-4xl lg:text-6xl xl:text-7xl font-medium leading-[1.05] tracking-tighter max-w-[720px] mb-10">
      Win on functionality,<br />
      <span class="text-fg-tertiary">not data model.</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="text-[17px] leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary max-w-[540px]">
      The durable advantage in software is shifting — from what you keep locked
      away to what you actually do with it. Open lexicons are how we think that
      shift gets built. Here is the argument.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 01 THE OLD MOAT -->
  <section class="fade-in py-16 border-t border-rule">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-10">01 &nbsp;/&nbsp; The old moat</p>
    <p class="text-2xl lg:text-4xl font-medium leading-snug tracking-tight max-w-[640px] mb-12">
      For twenty years, the moat was the data model.
    </p>
    <div class="max-w-[600px] space-y-5">
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        Own the schema, own the data inside it, and make leaving expensive.
        That was the whole game. You didn’t have to keep being the best product —
        you just had to make the exit costly enough that customers stayed.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        It produced a generation of software that stopped improving the moment it
        had captured enough data to be sticky. The value wasn’t in the experience.
        It was in the switching cost.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 02 OPEN LEXICONS -->
  <section class="fade-in py-16 border-t border-rule">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-10">02 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Open lexicons</p>
    <p class="text-2xl lg:text-4xl font-medium leading-snug tracking-tight max-w-[640px] mb-12">
      A Lexicon is a schema anyone can read and write against.
    </p>
    <div class="max-w-[600px] space-y-5">
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        On AT Protocol, data is defined by Lexicons — open, versioned schemas that
        describe records. When your data model is a Lexicon, it stops being a
        secret. Any app, any agent, any competitor can read it and build on it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        That sounds like giving away the store. It’s the opposite. An open schema
        turns your data from a vault into infrastructure — and infrastructure
        compounds. Every app that adopts your Lexicon makes it more valuable, more
        of a standard, harder to displace.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        The company that defines the schema an industry runs on holds a different,
        better kind of advantage than the one merely hoarding rows.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 03 WIN ON FUNCTIONALITY -->
  <section class="fade-in py-16 border-t border-rule">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-10">03 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Win on functionality</p>
    <p class="text-2xl lg:text-4xl font-medium leading-snug tracking-tight max-w-[640px] mb-12">
      When everyone can read the data, the contest moves to what you do with it.
    </p>
    <div class="max-w-[600px] space-y-5">
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        If your data is open, you can’t coast on lock-in. You keep customers by
        being genuinely better — faster, clearer, more useful — every day. That is
        a harder game, and a fairer one, and it rewards the exact thing users
        actually want: a great product.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        We think that’s where durable value is heading. Lock-in is fragile:
        regulators are prying it open, users expect portability, and AI agents
        route around any app whose data they can’t read. Functionality is not
        fragile. The best experience wins — and keeps winning, because it earns
        the win.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 border border-rule p-6 lg:p-8 max-w-[620px]">
      <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-4">
        In practice — <a href="/work/" class="border-b border-rule pb-px transition-colors duration-150 hover:text-fg hover:border-fg">Antiphony</a>
      </p>
      <p class="text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary mb-4">
        We build this way ourselves. Antiphony puts audio posts, replies, identity,
        and transcription on open Lexicons — shared infrastructure any app can read
        and write. Two different applications we’re building already run on it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        That’s exactly the point. Because both apps share the same audio data model,
        storing audio isn’t what makes anyone choose one over the other — it can’t
        be. The data model is table stakes. What you do with it is the product.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 04 WHY WE BELIEVE IT -->
  <section class="fade-in py-16 border-t border-b border-rule">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-widest text-fg-tertiary mb-10">04 &nbsp;/&nbsp; What it means for you</p>
    <div class="max-w-[600px] space-y-5">
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        Publish on open lexicons. Treat your data model as public infrastructure,
        not a vault. Then pour your energy into the one layer that stays
        defensible — the experience.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-fg-secondary">
        This is the bet we help companies make, and the reason Bird Candy exists:
        to make the open move well, and early, while it’s still an advantage rather
        than a scramble.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="fade-in pt-16 pb-20">
    <p class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-medium leading-snug tracking-tight max-w-[500px] mb-6">
      If this is the game you want to play, let’s talk.
    </p>
    <a
      href="/#contact"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm font-medium text-fg no-underline border-b border-rule pb-0.5 transition-[border-color] duration-150 hover:border-fg"
    >
      Get in touch &rarr;
    </a>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
